definition.value: The L-enantiomer of thyroxine.
A member of the class of benzaldehydes carrying methoxy and hydroxy substituents at positions 3 and 4 respectively.
The R-enantiomer of noradrenaline.

A member of the class of psoralens that is 7H-furo[3,2-g]chromen-7-one in which the 9 position is substituted by a methoxy group. It is a constituent of the fruits of Ammi majus. Like other psoralens, trioxsalen causes photosensitization of the skin. It is administered topically or orally in conjunction with UV-A for phototherapy treatment of vitiligo and severe psoriasis.
A piperidinium ion obtained by protonation of the piperidine nitrogen of ketanserin; major microspecies at pH 7.3.
A phosphate ion that is the conjugate base of hydrogenphosphate.

A compound having the structure RC#N; thus a C-substituted derivative of hydrocyanic acid, HC#N. In systematic nomenclature, the suffix nitrile denotes the triply bound #N atom, not the carbon atom attached to it.
A primary alcohol that is 1,3-thiazol-3-ium substituted by (4-amino-2-methylpyrimidin-5-yl)methyl, methyl and 2-hydroxyethyl groups at positions 3, 4 and 5, respectively.
A gluconate having D-configuration.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of phenylacetic acid.
A one-carbon compound consisting of a methine group triple bonded to a nitrogen atom
A member of the class of cobalamins that is vitamin B12 in which the cyano group is replaced by a 5'-deoxyadenos-5'-yl moiety. It is one of the two metabolically active form of vitamin B12.
A guanidinium ion obtained by protonation of both guanidino groups of streptidine; major species at pH 7.3.
A racemate composed of equimolar amounts of (R)- and (S)-nicotine.
An amino acid zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of baclofen.
A phenol substituted at position 4 by a 2-hydroxyethyl group.

An olefinic compound that is ethene is which a hydrogen at position 1 is replaced by a 4-carboxyphenyl group and a hydrogen at position 2 is replaced by a 5,5,8,8-tetramethyl-3-[(1H-pyrazol-1-yl)methyl]-5,6,7,8-tetrahydronaphthalen-2-yl group (the E-stereoisomer). It is a selective retinoic acid receptor gamma (RARgamma) agonist developed by Ipsen, to reduce the formation of new heterotopic ossification in adults and children with fibrodysplasia ossificans progressiva (FOP), a rare bone disorder.
A lactone having a six-membered lactone ring.
A dicarboxylic acid dianion resulting from the deprotonation of the two carboxy groups of 5-methyltetrahydrofolic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
Any polyunsaturated fatty acid carrying one or more hydroperoxy substituents.
Any fatty acid containing two carboxy groups.
Any fatty acid that contains 2 carboxylic groups. Major microspecies at pH 7.3
The S-enantiomer of tianeptine.
The R-enantiomer of tianeptine.
A member of the class of dibenzothiazepines that is 3-chloro-6-methyl-6,11-dihydrodibenzo[c,f][1,2]thiazepine 5,5-dioxide substituted by a (6-carboxyhexyl)amino group at position 11.
An inorganic calcium salt having silicate as the counterion.
A calcium salt that lacks C-H bonds
